---
import CaseStudy from '../../layouts/CaseStudy.astro';
---

<CaseStudy
  title="Migrating an engineering org from Jira to Linear"
  eyebrow="Branch · Spring 2026"
  summary="A six-week pilot with real engineers, not a vendor demo. The data made the case. 2.7× throughput per engineer, 87 to 93% cycle completion against the industry benchmark, and the team voting overwhelmingly to migrate."
  role="Sr. Director of Product Experience"
  duration="12 weeks (setup and pilot)"
  team="Eng, PM, Product Ops"
  outcome="Enterprise-scale rollout decision"
>
  <h2>The question wasn't Jira vs. Linear. It was what to invest in.</h2>

  <p>
    Our Jira instance had accumulated the kind of complexity every long-running enterprise
    deployment does. Non-standardized issue types, workflows, and fields across teams.
    Cross-team initiative visibility that didn't really exist because epics couldn't span
    team boundaries. Significant abandoned space alongside active work. The system was
    failing despite full adoption.
  </p>

  <p>
    The proposed fix was a contractor-led cleanup project measured in months of work. Before
    signing off, I wanted to test a different question:
    <strong>
      should we invest that remediation effort into fixing what we have, or into a platform
      that doesn't need fixing?
    </strong>
  </p>

  <h2>A real test, not a vendor demo</h2>

  <p>
    I designed a six-week live pilot. Not a sandbox. Not a sales engineering walkthrough.
    Real engineers doing real work, with the same engineers benchmarked in both systems.
  </p>

  <ul class="list-none pl-0 my-8 space-y-3">
    <li class="flex gap-4">
      <span class="font-mono text-orange">→</span>
      <span><strong>Pilot teams:</strong> A cross-functional pod of engineers and PMs, plus a documentation team, plus a design-systems pod</span>
    </li>
    <li class="flex gap-4">
      <span class="font-mono text-orange">→</span>
      <span><strong>Method:</strong> Before survey (Jira baseline), mid-cycle check-in, post-pilot final survey</span>
    </li>
    <li class="flex gap-4">
      <span class="font-mono text-orange">→</span>
      <span><strong>Benchmark:</strong> Before and after issue data from the same engineers in both Jira and Linear</span>
    </li>
    <li class="flex gap-4">
      <span class="font-mono text-orange">→</span>
      <span><strong>Integrations:</strong> Slack, GitHub, MCP, AI coding tools</span>
    </li>
  </ul>

  <p>
    I set five target metrics before the pilot started. Issue creation frequency, engineer
    satisfaction, cycle completion rate, percentage of work tracked, and issue resolution
    time. I also met with the vendor's solution engineering team to address concerns from
    internal dissenters before the cutover decision.
  </p>

  <!-- Big stat callout -->
  <div class="not-prose my-16 py-16 px-8 md:px-12 bg-navy-deep text-cream relative overflow-hidden">
    <div class="absolute top-6 left-8 font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.18em] text-cream/60">
      The Result
    </div>
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-12 items-center">
      <div>
        <p class="font-display text-[clamp(5rem,15vw,12rem)] leading-none text-orange">
          2.7×
        </p>
      </div>
      <div>
        <p class="font-display text-2xl md:text-3xl text-cream leading-tight mb-4">
          More issues completed per engineer per week in Linear vs. Jira.
        </p>
        <p class="font-mono text-sm text-cream/70">
          Same engineers. Same work. Source: Jira "Status Category Changed" field and
          Linear export. The vendor's cross-customer benchmark is 2×. We hit 2.7×.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <h2>Five metrics. Four hits. One partial. Zero misses.</h2>

  <p>The pilot delivered against every target I set:</p>

  <div class="not-prose my-12 space-y-4">
    {[
      {
        metric: 'Issue creation frequency',
        target: 'Target: 2× increase',
        result: '2.7× throughput per engineer, per week',
        status: 'HIT',
      },
      {
        metric: 'Engineer satisfaction',
        target: 'Target: 4.0+ in Linear',
        result: '5.0/5 overall. Every dimension above 4.0.',
        status: 'HIT',
      },
      {
        metric: 'Cycle completion rate',
        target: 'Target: stable or improved',
        result: '100%, 87%, 93% across first three cycles. Planning 4 cycles ahead.',
        status: 'HIT',
      },
      {
        metric: '% of work tracked',
        target: 'Target: 80%+',
        result: 'Four of five respondents at 75 to 100%. Most issues tied to a project.',
        status: 'HIT',
      },
      {
        metric: 'Issue resolution time',
        target: 'Target: faster',
        result: 'Median work time under 2 days in Linear. Jira baseline unavailable in export.',
        status: 'PARTIAL',
      },
    ].map((row) => (
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-12 gap-4 py-5 border-b border-ink/10 items-start">
        <div class="md:col-span-3">
          <p class="font-display text-lg text-ink">{row.metric}</p>
          <p class="font-mono text-xs text-ink-muted mt-1">{row.target}</p>
        </div>
        <div class="md:col-span-7 text-ink-soft">{row.result}</div>
        <div class="md:col-span-2 md:text-right">
          <span
            class={`font-mono text-xs uppercase tracking-[0.15em] px-3 py-1 ${
              row.status === 'HIT' ? 'bg-orange text-cream' : 'bg-cream-deep text-ink'
            }`}
          >
            {row.status}
          </span>
        </div>
      </div>
    ))}
  </div>

  <h2>Every engineer improved. Even the one who preferred Jira.</h2>

  <p>
    Throughput gains weren't concentrated in early adopters or power users. Every pilot
    engineer measured higher issue completion in Linear than in Jira, with individual
    gains ranging widely. The engineer who rated Linear lowest in mid-pilot still
    completed more work in it.
  </p>

  <p>
    Survey deltas told the same story. Across every dimension I measured (ease of creation,
    ability to triage, trust in the data, roadmap visibility, manager visibility, overall
    satisfaction) Linear improved on Jira. Overall satisfaction was the largest delta.
  </p>

  <blockquote>
    "Please let us keep using Linear. I desperately do not want to go back to Jira."
    <br />
    <span class="not-italic font-mono text-sm text-ink-muted">
      Pilot engineer, post-pilot survey
    </span>
  </blockquote>

  <h2>A capability decision, not a savings decision</h2>

  <p>
    The financial case wasn't a savings story. It was a capability story. I modeled three
    scenarios for leadership: staying with the incumbent stack and funding the cleanup
    project, switching tools with the existing scope intact, and switching while
    consolidating a redundant adjacent tool.
  </p>

  <p>
    The third scenario delivered both the lowest cost and the strongest capability profile.
    But the framing that mattered to executives wasn't the line item. It was that we were
    choosing between investing in a tool that needed fixing versus a platform that could
    enable downstream automation we couldn't get from the incumbent. Capability decisions
    survive procurement cycles. Savings decisions get re-litigated.
  </p>

  <p>
    Importantly, the 2.7× throughput was measured before integrations activated. Call
    summarization to issues, support ticket triage, internal request handling, and release
    automation were all post-migration capabilities. The pilot result was the floor, not
    the ceiling.
  </p>

  <h2>What I did, what changed</h2>

  <p>
    I owned the end-to-end pilot. Design, execution, and recommendation. JQL-scoped sprint
    exports, CSV mapping logic for the import, importer evaluation across multiple paths,
    pilot team selection, benchmark methodology, before-and-after survey design, dissenter
    review meetings, and the final executive recommendation.
  </p>

  <p>
    The migration moved forward as a full org cut-over with white-glove onboarding from
    the vendor's customer success team, sequenced through engineering and product first,
    then through downstream functions, with an adjacent tool evaluated in parallel for the
    consolidation decision.
  </p>

  <h2>Why this case study</h2>

  <p>
    Most "design leader leads tooling decision" stories are project-management fables.
    This one shows what design leadership actually looks like at the executive level.
    Framing the right question (capability vs. cost). Designing a defensible test
    methodology. Holding the test accountable to pre-set metrics. Presenting the result
    as a business case rather than a feature wishlist. And managing the dissent that
    inevitably surfaces when the data is too good.
  </p>

  <p>
    Design leadership isn't just about what ships. It's about what gets decided.
  </p>
</CaseStudy>
